, military forces, and police; respect for the rule of law (and a residual contempt for it as a result of colonial associations); underdeveloped and unbalanced economies; hostility toward the West, including American "dollar-imperialism," and a hypersensitivity to criticism from that quarter. Mr. Gower continues with an assessment of what has happened to these legacies since independence and what seems likely to happen to them in the next few decades. His central concern is the challenge thus implied for the indigenous legal professions, but his study has far wider implications. In conclusion Mr. Gower describes how the legal professions were organized at the time of independence in the various countries and what progress has been made in producing the kinds of lawyers needed to solve the urgent problems these countries face. He suggests what the United States can and should-and occasionally what it should not-do to help.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aAfrique, politique interieure, Droit. 0aColonies. 0aGrande-Bretagne, questions coloniales. 0aPolitical science. 0aPractice of law. 0aRecht. 4aAfrica -- Politics and government. 4aLaw -- Africa. 4aLawyers -- Africa. 4aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / General. 4aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Ethnic Studies / African American Studies. 7aLAW / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHUP e-dition: Complete eBook Packagez9783110353488oZDB-23-HCO08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHUP e-dition: Law & Political Science eBook Packagez9783110353495oZDB-23-HLP08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHUP eBook Package Archive 1893-1999z97831104422120 cprintz978067449239440uhttps://doi.org/10.4159/harvard.978067449240040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780674492400423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/978067449240